conversation.utterance: isn't it something to do with fat content of the bird?

Wow! That is correct! Duck handles high heat so well for two reasons.  First, the meat all over is on the darker side, giving it a richer, oilier texture that can better withstand the drying effects of high temperatures. Second, and even more important, is the duck's luxuriously fatty skin, which insulates the meat and bathes it in mouth-coating rendered fat, ensuring each bite is unctuous.
